{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524165"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.25,0.11,0.32,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54019"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6610"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3813"},{"type":"tags","id":"3815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54019"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of worsening abdominal pain, distension, and constipation. He has not passed stool or flatus for three days. He has a medical history of hypertension and appendicectomy 30 years ago. He takes amlodipine for his blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended and tympanic with generalised tenderness but no guarding. Bowel sounds are high-pitched and tinkling. Digital rectal examination reveals an empty rectum with no masses. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopic decompression","Conservative management with nasogastric decompression","Laparoscopic right hemicolectomy","Immediate laparotomy and resection","Colonic stenting as a bridge to surgery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of large bowel obstruction, which is confirmed by CT scan showing an obstructing lesion at the junction of the sigmoid and descending colon. In this scenario, the most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate laparotomy and resection\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach allows for definitive treatment of the obstruction, removal of the likely malignant lesion, and prevention of potential complications such as perforation or ischaemia. The presence of abdominal tenderness can be a worrying sign in such circumstances, suggestive of ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonic stenting as a bridge to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered in selected cases of malignant large bowel obstruction, particularly in high-risk patients or those with metastatic disease. However, in this case, with an otherwise healthy patient presenting with acute obstruction, immediate surgical intervention is preferred to relieve the obstruction and obtain a definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with nasogastric decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for large bowel obstruction caused by a likely malignant lesion. This approach would not address the underlying cause and could lead to worsening of the patient\u0027s condition or complications such as perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for large bowel obstruction caused by a tumour. It carries a high risk of perforation and is generally ineffective in providing long-term relief in cases of mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic right hemicolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in this case as the CT scan shows the obstructing lesion to be in the left colon (sigmoid/descending colon junction). Right hemicolectomy is reserved for lesions in the right colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of large bowel obstruction due to suspected colorectal cancer, CT scanning is the imaging modality of choice. It not only confirms the diagnosis but also helps in staging the disease and identifying potential metastases. The definitive treatment involves surgical resection of the affected bowel segment with adequate margins, along with regional lymphadenectomy. The specific surgical approach (open vs. laparoscopic, primary anastomosis vs. stoma) depends on various factors including the patient\u0027s condition, the location of the tumour, and the extent of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Large bowel obstruction due to colorectal cancer requires prompt surgical intervention.","CT scan is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing and staging colorectal cancer.","Colonic stenting can be considered as a bridge to surgery in selected cases of malignant large bowel obstruction."],"references":["Catena, F, De Simone B, Coccolini F, et al. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg 2019. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31168315/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20869"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21056"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20869"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zc4lLqP1RvO4He55IV3d7qaYYWHnyV.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zc4lLqP1RvO4He55IV3d7qaYYWHnyV.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":510,"height":421}},{"type":"media","id":"21056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21056"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/inONEpuUv8xqkcF8aHq8PCuhTny2aX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/inONEpuUv8xqkcF8aHq8PCuhTny2aX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":510,"height":421}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39491"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T23:42:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T19:19:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6610"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54019"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta